<DOC><DOCNO> AP901031-0223 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-10-31-90 1054EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-Earns-GM 1stLd-Writethru f0011 10-31 0398</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Earns-GM, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0011,0479</SECOND><HEAD>GM Posts Nearly $2 Billion Loss for Third Quarter with Charge</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 10 new grafs to UPDATE with GM earnings. Picks up4th graf pvs, Among the ...</NOTE><BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   General Motors Corp. today reported a $2 billionloss for the third quarter including a one-time charge of $2.1billion for closing four assembly plants and related expenses.   The loss amounts to $3.54 per common share. GM had earned $516.9million, or 72 cents a share, in the July-September quarter a yearearlier.   Without the charge, GM's earnings for the latest period stood at$109 million, down 78.9 percent from earnings a year earlier.   GM's third-quarter revenue rose 6.9 percent to $30.8 billionfrom $28.8 billion last year.   The $2.1 billion charge includes costs associated with theformal shutting down of four assembly plants the were idled duringthe past three years. Those car plants are near Kansas City, Mo.;Framingham, Mass.; Pontiac, Mich.; and Atlanta.   The company said the charge also contemplates the closing orconsolidating of other plants and warehouses during the next threeyears. The company previously had announced it planned to idletruck assembly plants in Scarborough, Ontario; Lordstown, Ohio; andPontiac.   ``The restructuring is a major element in GM's long-termstrategic plan to improve the competitiveness and profitability ofits North American operations,'' GM Chairman Robert Stempel said ina statement today.   Including the charge, GM said it lost $368.7 million, or $1.20 ashare, in the first nine months of the year compared with a profitof $3.52 billion, or $5.32 a share, in the first nine months of1989.   Revenues for the January-September period were $94.8 billionthis year, down 0.8 percent from $95.6 billion a year ago.   On Tuesday, GM's major subsidiaries reported their third-quarterresults.   Among the subsidiaries, General Motors Acceptance Corp. reportedthe largest jump, 24.7 percent. Electronic Data Systems Corp. saidits profits rose 17 percent and GM-Hughes Electronics Corp.reported earnings up 7 percent.   GMAC said it earned $293 million during the three months endedSept. 30, compared with $235 million for the third quarter of 1989.   EDS said it had net income of $128.4 million, or 54 cents ashare, for the period, up from $110.9 million, or 46 cents a share,for July-September 1989.   Revenues for the quarter rose to $1.53 billion from $1.37billion in the third quarter of 1989, the company said.   GM Hughes Electronics said it had net income of $158.1 million,or 40 cents a share, for the quarter, up from $147.8 million, or 37cents a share, a year earlier.   Revenues rose to $2.93 billion for the period from $2.58 billionin the third quarter of 1989, the company said.</TEXT></DOC>